{
  "doc_id": "59971",
  "text": "It is possible that SRC tasks are not particularly well-suited to studying individual differences (Hedge et al., 2017) , and experimental work may be more effective at studying how social factors influence automatic imitation. To this end, several recent studies have shown that social factors can influence SRC measures of imitation [CITATION_1] . SRC measures of imitation are increased in situations that promote affiliation through eye contact [CITATION_2] , group membership [CITATION_3] , and facial expressions [CITATION_4] , as well as when interacting with more human-like, rather than robotic, agents [CITATION_5] [CITATION_6] [CITATION_7] . Other work has shown that when prosocial attitudes are generated [CITATION_8] [CITATION_9] , or prosocial gestures are signalled , imitation increases. These studies suggest that the compatibility effect is modulated by social factors in a broadly corresponding manner to findings from overt measures of behavioural copying [CITATION_10] . These results have led to theories that suggest an opportunity for social reward can increase imitation .",
